# Classic Image Builds (SPI Injection)

## Overview

The principle function of the wrangler is to automate interactions
with notebook repos and their curators and to that end it can be
broken down into three main aspects:

1. The wrangler scrapes a collection of notebook repos for the
package requirements needed to run specified notebooks;  typically
each notebook defines a requirements.txt file and the wrangler
solves constraints for the union of all of them producing a locked
(fully pinned) package list for a notebook "mission" environment.
Further,  it fetches and includes a refdata_dependencies.yaml file
that the repo can use to define required data and environment variables.
Thus the basic nature of part 1 is to define and install local
versions of an environment.  As the culmination of this process,
running the wrangler on the installed environment with --test-imports
helps verify that all of the packages explicitly required by notebooks
import successfully.

2. The wrangler interacts with the science-platform-images (SPI) repo
to inject the requirements determined by (1) above.  This is the automated
version of a curator feeding the development team a package list via
Jira which the developer then deposits into science-platform-images
at the correct locations.  It's the role of science-platform-images
to build notebook images according to the wrangler spec requirements.
Thus for phase 2,  the wrangler uses a local clone of science-platform-images
to perform code updates,  and has convenience functions to build the
resulting configuration and also to create and push a pr to science-platform-images
to record the release.

3. Once science-platform-images has been updated with new requirements using
steps (1) and (2) above, the image build and deployment process proceeds
more-or-less in classic fashion.  Consequently familiar approaches to
configuring, building, testing, pushing to ECR, and re-tagging an image to
promote it should work.  Since science-platform-images doesn't know about
the platform's ECR registry,  the built image needs to be retagged and pushed
to ECR semi-manually.  Once the image is in ECR,  it needs to be tagged
appropriately for use in some (TEST?) SDLC and the hub profiles need to be
adjusted as needed to offer that image to SDLC users.  As an additional
step to deploying some releases,  the developer should log in as admin and
run the wrangler data installation mode which will install the data specified
by the notebook repos under /teams/admin/nbw-pantry/...  Wrangler defined
environment variables will point to this instalation location and will be
both built into the environment kernel definition and available for terminal
sessions.  Once a notebook session has been started and the environment and
data are fully installed,  it should be possible to re-run import and notebook
tests using /opt/environments/test.
